    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3529578114" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3529578114" />
    <a title="Francis Fabian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66615691-francis-fabian"><img alt="Francis Fabian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1491368676p2/66615691.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3529578114?book_show_action=true">Sep 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Francis Fabian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Francis Fabian" href="/user/show/66615691-francis-fabian">Francis Fabian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3529578114" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15230380704352035167">Ok, I enjoyed it. As you know this is the sequel to Wells&apos; The Time Machine. Baxter attempts to write in the style of Wells&apos; narrator and I feel he does an excellent job. It is a long book. But short chapters makes it go quickly. No spoilers but here are a few of the ideas encountered. Multiverse, parallel universes, infinity, dyson spheres (lots of them), super intelligent morlocks, super intelligent machines, etc. Lots of excitement. The last section of the book is very wordy about the above c</span>
  <span id="freeText15230380704352035167" style="display:none">Ok, I enjoyed it. As you know this is the sequel to Wells' The Time Machine. Baxter attempts to write in the style of Wells' narrator and I feel he does an excellent job. It is a long book. But short chapters makes it go quickly. No spoilers but here are a few of the ideas encountered. Multiverse, parallel universes, infinity, dyson spheres (lots of them), super intelligent morlocks, super intelligent machines, etc. Lots of excitement. The last section of the book is very wordy about the above concepts. It read a lot like Stapledon who was more of a philosopher than an SF author. I quite like Stapledon so it worked for me. I think it is a well written sequel. Very different to the original. Because of the multiverse the idea of morlocks &amp; eloi splitting because of the sociopolitical problems since the industrial age is barely considered, but that was ok for me. The original idea from Wells was really too simplistic to me. Not that I am an expert on evolution or human behaviour. So, if you enjoyed The Time Machine but want more I'd recommend The Time Ships.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15230380704352035167" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

